  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can someone build a product based on an idea he pitched to his ex company, if the company never cared to productize it?",
  "response": "In general, the ability to develop a product based on an idea pitched to a former employer can depend on several factors, including the nature of the idea, any existing agreements signed with the company (like non-compete or confidentiality agreements), and whether the idea was considered proprietary or part of the company's intellectual property.\n\nHere are some considerations:\n\n1. **Employment Agreement**: Review any employment or separation agreements you signed. These documents might contain clauses related to non-compete, non-disclosure, or ownership of ideas developed during employment. If the idea was developed as part of your job, the company may have a claim to it.\n\n2. **Intellectual Property**: If the idea was developed using company resources or during work hours, it might be considered the company's intellectual property. However, if the idea was conceived outside of work and not directly related to your job responsibilities, it might be considered your personal intellectual property.\n\n3. **Non-disclosure Agreements (NDA)**: If you signed an NDA, you may be restricted from using or disclosing confidential information learned during your employment. Ensure that developing the product does not violate any confidentiality obligations.\n\n4. **Non-compete Clauses**: Check if there are any non-compete clauses that prevent you from engaging in similar business activities for a certain period after leaving the company. These clauses can vary by jurisdiction and may not always be enforceable, but they should be considered.\n\n5. **Company's Interest**: If the company showed no interest in developing the idea and did not pursue it, they might have relinquished any claim to it. However, this does not automatically mean you have the right to develop it; it depends on the factors mentioned above.\n\n6. **Legal Advice**: Due to the complexity of intellectual property and employment law, it is advisable to consult with a legal professional who can provide guidance specific to your situation and jurisdiction.\n\nIf after reviewing these factors you believe you have the right to develop the product, you can proceed with building it. However, maintaining transparency about the origin of the idea and being prepared to address any potential legal challenges from your former employer is important.",
